		<div class="row">
				<div class="col-md-8 text-justify gtco-heading">
					<h2>Diodon - Puffer Fish</h2>
					<p style="margin-bottom:30px;">The Puffer fish have a sturdy body with a much large, bulky, bulbous and wide head. Their size can reach a length close to 20 cm in the wild.
						The most distinctive characteristic are the innumerable thorns which cover their body except for the mouth. Their eyes are quite large and black, with bluish lines, being rounded by a golden or copper iris. 
						They lack the pelvic fins, and their dorsal fin which is tiny is located at the bottom close to the caudal appendix. The dorsal and pectoral fins are highly effective motor organs that give Puffer fish a very agile swimming, and to quickly modify and change their direction with ease.
					</p>
				</div>
				
					<div class="col-md-4">
					<img src="images/pufferfish2.jpg" style = "width:100%; height:300px;;">
				</div>
			</div>
					<div class="row">
					<div class="col-md-4">
					<img src="images/pufferfish3.jpg" style = "width:100%; height:300px;;">
				</div>
				<div class="col-md-8 text-justify gtco-heading">
					<h2>Habitat and conservation</h2>
					<p>They are generally circumtropical in distribution being benthic around the corals. They are mostly found in marine waters, some in brackish waters and some in fresh waters.
						The adults are generally found in holes and crevices in the inshore areas including lagoons, caves, shipwrecks, reefs, and ledges, and are also found in seamount areas. They have been found in depths of about 50 meters but can be seen most commonly between 5 and 40 meters. 
						The juveniles are pelagic until reaching 20 cm in length, becoming benthic or floating thereafter.
					</p>
				</div>
				
			</div>
		
