							<h1>Did you know? </h1>
	<h2> The Puffer fish do not have scales and their skin is thick and rough, as some might have spines on their skin. 
		All the Puffer fish share one characteristic, that is the ability to puff up, which is what gives them their name. They can puff up to two or three times their normal size. 
		When they are threatened, they can ingest huge amount of water, and air sometimes, which increases their body size and turn them into large ball-like creatures that scares the predators. 
		Puffer fish contain a neurotoxin called tetrodotoxin that can be about 1000 times stronger than cyanide. As they puff up, the toxin is released on their skin. 
	One puffer fish contains toxins that can kill about 25 human adults.
	In Japan, Puffer fish is a delicacy called fugu and the chefs who have trained for at least 3 years can only prepare them.
	The have four teeth which they use to open clams and mussels.

							<!-- <a href="http://freehtml5.co" target="_blank">FreeHTML5.co</a> --> </h2>
